The 16 MHz crystal oscillator provides the clock signal required for the microcontroller operation. It determines the execution speed of instructions and timing functions. A stable crystal ensures accurate timing, communication, and overall system performance.
4. 22 pF Capacitors Connected to OSC1 and OSC2
Electrical Specifications
Capacitance: 22 pF each
Connection: One from OSC1 to GND and one from OSC2 to GND
The two 22 pF capacitors act as load capacitors for the 16 MHz crystal oscillator. They help the crystal start oscillating correctly and maintain frequency stability. These capacitors reduce noise and ensure reliable clock generation for the PIC16F877A.
5.MCLR Reset Circuit :
The MCLR reset circuit consists of a pull-up resistor, push-button switch, and capacitor connected to the MCLR pin of the PIC16F877A 
1. Pull-up Resistor (Typically 10 kΩ)
 The resistor keeps the MCLR pin at logic HIGH (5 V) during normal operation. Since MCLR is an active-low reset pin, keeping it high allows the microcontroller to run normally.




2. Push Button Reset Switch
 When the push button is pressed, the MCLR pin is connected to GND, making it logic LOW. This resets the PIC16F877A and restarts program execution from the beginning.
3. Debouncing Capacitor (Typically 100 nF)
 The capacitor filters noise and prevents false resets caused by switch bouncing or power supply disturbances. It also provides a short delay during power-up, ensuring the supply voltage becomes stable before the microcontroller starts operating.

